\begin{document}

\title{Approximating Unconditional Cavity Displacement in Dispersive Circuit QED}
\author{Autonomous cQED Research Platform}
\affiliation{Shyam Shankar Quantum Circuits Group}
\date{\today}

\begin{abstract}
An ideal cavity drive is often modeled as the unconditional gate
\(
I_q \otimes D(\alpha)
\),
but a realistic dispersive qubit-cavity system does not realize that map automatically once the qubit is allowed to occupy \(|e\rangle\) or a superposition. We benchmark five control families for this task: naive single-tone displacement, fast broadband single-tone pulses, two-tone branch-compensated displacement, echoed displacement with qubit \(\pi\) pulses, and hardware-aware optimal control. Using a dispersive Hamiltonian hierarchy that includes the leading dispersive shift, a higher-order correction, cavity self-Kerr, and hardware filtering in the constrained optimization benchmark, we find that the naive square pulse becomes strongly conditional once \(|\chi|T\) is no longer small: at \(\alpha=1\) and \(T=\SI{80}{\nano\second}\), the branch mismatch reaches \(\delta\alpha=0.686\) and the vacuum superposition fidelity falls to \(0.770\). A \(\SI{5}{\nano\second}\) Gaussian pulse suppresses the mismatch to \(0.0539\), but a realistic low-pass filter collapses the achieved displacement unless the pulse is precompensated. The best simple, physically interpretable protocol is a \(\SI{20}{\nano\second}\) two-tone pulse, which yields \(\delta\alpha=8.15\times10^{-4}\), vacuum-branch fidelities above \(0.999996\), and residual entanglement below \(10^{-5}\) bits. The best overall mean fidelity on a broader state-test set comes from a constrained hardware-aware optimal-control waveform, which reaches \(0.958\) mean state fidelity at \(\SI{40}{\nano\second}\). A practical echoed displacement using vacuum-calibrated qubit inversions is not competitive because the inserted \(\pi\) pulse is itself manifold dependent once the cavity is populated.
\end{abstract}

\maketitle

\section{Introduction}

In bosonic control protocols for circuit quantum electrodynamics, cavity drives are frequently treated as ideal displacements that act only on the oscillator degree of freedom~\cite{blais2004cavity,blais2021circuit}. At the gate-language level, one writes
\begin{equation}
U_{\mathrm{target}} = I_q \otimes D(\alpha),
\end{equation}
where \(D(\alpha)\) is the usual displacement operator. This abstraction is useful, but it hides the central difficulty of the dispersive regime: the cavity resonance depends on the qubit state through the dispersive pull \(\chi\), so a pulse calibrated in one qubit manifold is generically detuned in the other~\cite{schuster2007resolving,nguyen2012dispersive}.

Once the qubit is allowed to begin in \(|e\rangle\) or in a superposition, the conditional cavity dynamics can no longer be ignored. The final cavity amplitudes may differ in magnitude and phase between the two qubit branches, and a qubit superposition may emerge entangled with the cavity. Higher-order dispersive terms, cavity self-Kerr, finite pulse duration, bandwidth limits, and hardware transfer effects can then amplify or reshape the failure of the unconditional picture.

The present study asks a practical version of the problem: what control strategy most accurately approximates \(I_q \otimes D(\alpha)\) under a realistic dispersive Hamiltonian, and when should an experimentalist stop treating a cavity pulse as an unconditional displacement at all? We focus on five protocol families: a naive single-tone pulse, fast broadband single-tone pulses, two-tone branch compensation, echoed displacement, and a bounded hardware-aware optimal-control benchmark. The comparison is made on common state and entanglement diagnostics rather than on a single branch-calibration metric alone.

\section{System, Control Protocols, and Metrics}
\label{sec:methods}

\subsection{Hamiltonian hierarchy}

We model a dispersive transmon-cavity system using the Hamiltonian
\begin{align}
\frac{H}{\hbar} &=
\omega_c a^\dagger a + \frac{\omega_q}{2}\sigma_z
+ \chi a^\dagger a \sigma_z
+ \chi' a^\dagger a (a^\dagger a - 1) \Pi_e
\nonumber\\
&\quad
+ \frac{K}{2} a^{\dagger 2} a^2
+ \epsilon(t) a^\dagger + \epsilon^*(t) a,
\label{eq:fullham}
\end{align}
where \(a\) is the cavity lowering operator, \(\Pi_e\) projects onto the excited qubit manifold, \(\chi\) is the leading dispersive shift, \(\chi'\) is the higher-order dispersive correction, and \(K\) is the cavity self-Kerr coefficient. Simulations are performed in the bare-frequency rotating frame, so the branch dependence appears explicitly through the dispersive terms and the drive envelope \(\epsilon(t)\).

Four levels of realism are used:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item a minimal dispersive model with \(\chi\) only,
  \item a higher-order model with \(\chi\) and \(\chi'\),
  \item a full model with \(\chi\), \(\chi'\), and \(K\),
  \item a hardware-aware optimal-control benchmark that further includes a low-pass transfer model, amplitude limiting, and boundary smoothing in the control synthesis.
\end{enumerate}

The default parameters are representative of current transmon-cavity experiments~\cite{koch2007transmon,blais2021circuit}:
\(\omega_q/2\pi=\SI{6.150}{\giga\hertz}\),
\(\omega_c/2\pi=\SI{5.241}{\giga\hertz}\),
\(\alpha/2\pi=\SI{-255}{\mega\hertz}\),
\(\chi/2\pi=\SI{-2.84}{\mega\hertz}\),
\(\chi'/2\pi=\SI{-21}{\kilo\hertz}\),
and \(K/2\pi=\SI{-28}{\kilo\hertz}\).
The transmon is truncated to three or four levels depending on the validation spot check, the cavity is truncated to \(12\) to \(18\) levels depending on the protocol, and the default propagation step is \(\Delta t = \SI{0.5}{\nano\second}\).

\subsection{Analytic preliminary}

For a fixed qubit branch \(b \in \{g,e\}\), the cavity sees an effective detuning \(\Delta_b\), so the branch displacement after a drive \(\epsilon(t)\) is
\begin{equation}
\alpha_b(T) = -i \int_0^T \epsilon(t) e^{-i \Delta_b (T-t)} dt.
\label{eq:branchalpha}
\end{equation}
For a square pulse of complex amplitude \(\epsilon\),
\begin{equation}
\alpha_b(T)=\epsilon\frac{1-e^{-i\Delta_b T}}{\Delta_b},
\label{eq:squarebranch}
\end{equation}
which reduces to the ideal displacement \(-i\epsilon T\) only in the small-detuning limit \(|\Delta_b|T \ll 1\). This immediately predicts the central failure mode of the naive pulse: one branch remains near resonance while the other rotates in phase space and misses the target amplitude.

For a qubit superposition input, the final state has the form
\begin{equation}
\frac{|g\rangle |\psi_g\rangle + |e\rangle |\psi_e\rangle}{\sqrt{2}},
\end{equation}
so the residual qubit-cavity entanglement is controlled by the branch overlap \(|\langle \psi_g | \psi_e \rangle|\). A protocol may therefore appear successful on \(|g\rangle\) and \(|e\rangle\) separately while still failing as an unconditional operation on a superposition input.

\subsection{Protocol families}

\paragraph*{Naive single-tone displacement.}
The baseline pulse is a single carrier at the nominal cavity frequency with envelope \(f(t)\),
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{\mathrm{1t}}(t) = \epsilon_0 f(t),
\end{equation}
where square, Gaussian, and cosine envelopes are compared. The target area is chosen so that the resonant branch ideally implements \(D(\alpha_{\mathrm{target}})\).

\paragraph*{Fast broadband single-tone displacement.}
The same single-tone structure is used, but the duration is shortened so that the spectral width of the pulse exceeds the branch splitting. This is the simplest physical attempt to make the displacement effectively unconditional.

\paragraph*{Two-tone branch-compensated displacement.}
Two carriers are applied at the branch frequencies,
\begin{equation}
\epsilon_{\mathrm{2t}}(t) =
\epsilon_g(t)e^{-i\omega_{c,g} t}
+ \epsilon_e(t)e^{-i\omega_{c,e} t},
\label{eq:twotone}
\end{equation}
and the complex weights are solved from the simulated branch response matrix so that both branches end as close as possible to the same target displacement.

\paragraph*{Echoed displacement.}
The echoed construction uses a symmetric sequence
\begin{equation}
D_1 \rightarrow X_\pi \rightarrow D_2 \rightarrow X_\pi,
\end{equation}
with the intent of canceling the first-order dispersive phase. In the present study the qubit inversion is implemented by a practical Gaussian-DRAG pulse calibrated in the vacuum manifold.

\paragraph*{Hardware-aware optimal control.}
The final family optimizes two cavity quadratures directly under the full model using a constrained GRAPE formulation~\cite{khaneja2005grape,cqed_sim}. The optimization includes a first-order low-pass model, an instantaneous amplitude bound, and smooth boundary windows, and it is trained on a representative set of qubit and cavity input states rather than on vacuum alone.

\subsection{Metrics and validation states}

The protocol comparison uses five required diagnostics.

\paragraph*{Branch mismatch.}
The primary branch metric is
\begin{equation}
\delta \alpha = |\alpha_g - \alpha_e|,
\end{equation}
where \(\alpha_g\) and \(\alpha_e\) are extracted from the final cavity expectation values in the two qubit branches.

\paragraph*{Residual entanglement.}
For qubit superposition inputs, the entanglement is quantified by the qubit entropy
\begin{equation}
S(\rho_q) = - \mathrm{Tr}(\rho_q \log_2 \rho_q).
\end{equation}

\paragraph*{State fidelity to the ideal displaced target.}
For each input \(|\psi_i\rangle\), we compute
\begin{equation}
F_i = |\langle \psi_i^{\mathrm{ideal}} | \psi_i^{\mathrm{sim}} \rangle|^2,
\end{equation}
with \(|\psi_i^{\mathrm{ideal}}\rangle = (I_q \otimes D(\alpha_{\mathrm{target}})) |\psi_i\rangle\).
The headline broad-set metric is the mean over the explicit test set,
\begin{equation}
\bar{F} = \frac{1}{N}\sum_{i=1}^N F_i.
\end{equation}

\paragraph*{State test set.}
The qubit states are \(|g\rangle\), \(|e\rangle\), \((|g\rangle+|e\rangle)/\sqrt{2}\), and \((|g\rangle+i|e\rangle)/\sqrt{2}\). The cavity states are \(|0\rangle\), \(|1\rangle\), \(|2\rangle\), \(|3\rangle\), and a modest coherent state. The optimal-control benchmark is compared on the same broad family of states.

\paragraph*{Wigner agreement.}
For representative success and failure cases, the reduced cavity state is compared to the ideal displaced cavity state both visually through the Wigner function and quantitatively through the cavity trace distance.

\section{Results}
\label{sec:results}

\subsection{Naive single-tone displacement fails for superposition inputs}

Figure~\ref{fig:branch} compares the branch mismatch for the naive and two-tone protocols over the duration and target-amplitude sweep. The naive square pulse is almost branch independent only in the short-duration corner. By \(\alpha=1\) and \(T=\SI{80}{\nano\second}\), the simulated final branch amplitudes are
\begin{align}
\alpha_g &= 0.9961 + 0.0036 i, \\
\alpha_e &= 0.6783 + 0.6114 i,
\end{align}
so the mismatch reaches \(\delta\alpha = 0.6859\). The ground branch is still nearly ideal, with fidelity \(0.999960\), but the excited branch fidelity drops to \(0.622737\).

The more important failure is visible on superposition inputs. For the initial state \((|g\rangle + |e\rangle)/\sqrt{2} \otimes |0\rangle\), the same naive pulse produces fidelity \(0.770319\) and residual entanglement \(0.482920\) bits. The operation is therefore not merely miscalibrated; it is genuinely conditional.

\begin{figure}[tb]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{../figures/unconditional_branch_mismatch.pdf}
  \caption{Branch-resolved displacement mismatch \(\delta\alpha\) for the naive single-tone pulse (left) and the two-tone compensated pulse (right). Both panels use the same target-amplitude and duration grids. The naive protocol becomes strongly conditional as the pulse duration approaches and exceeds the dispersive timescale, whereas the two-tone construction suppresses the mismatch across the same region.}
  \label{fig:branch}
\end{figure}

The duration dependence follows the expected \(|\chi|T\) story. For the naive square pulse at \(\alpha=1\), the superposition fidelity decreases from \(0.994\) at \(\SI{5}{\nano\second}\) to \(0.978\) at \(\SI{20}{\nano\second}\), \(0.770\) at \(\SI{80}{\nano\second}\), and \(0.563\) at \(\SI{160}{\nano\second}\), while the entanglement grows from \(8.5\times10^{-3}\) bits to \(0.792\) bits over the same range. Since \(1/|\chi| = \SI{56.0}{\nano\second}\) for the present parameters, the onset of strong conditionality at tens of nanoseconds is exactly what the analytic estimate suggests.

\subsection{Fast pulses reduce conditionality, but filters remove usable displacement}

Figure~\ref{fig:entfilter}(a) shows the residual entanglement for the three fast single-tone envelope families together with the echoed and two-tone protocols. The best fast single-tone result in the sweep is a \(\SI{5}{\nano\second}\) Gaussian pulse, which yields
\begin{equation}
\delta\alpha = 0.0539,\quad F_{+x}=0.997743,\quad S=8.62\times10^{-3}\ \mathrm{bits}.
\end{equation}
This is the clearest evidence that a sufficiently broadband pulse can be effectively unconditional in the minimal dispersive sense.

The caveat appears once transfer effects are included. Figure~\ref{fig:entfilter}(b) shows that a low-pass filter preserves the small branch mismatch of the \(\SI{5}{\nano\second}\) Gaussian only by suppressing the achieved displacement itself. After a \(\SI{40}{\mega\hertz}\) low-pass filter, both branch fidelities collapse to about \(0.782\) because the pulse area is no longer sufficient to realize the target displacement. ``Make it fast'' is therefore not a complete strategy unless the hardware distortion is also calibrated or precompensated.

\begin{figure}[tb]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{../figures/unconditional_superposition_entanglement.pdf}
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{../figures/unconditional_filter_tradeoff.pdf}
  \caption{Top: residual entanglement for the vacuum superposition input \((|g\rangle + |e\rangle)/\sqrt{2} \otimes |0\rangle\) as a function of duration for the main protocol families. Bottom: the single-tone tradeoff between branch mismatch and pulse bandwidth, with and without a \(\SI{40}{\mega\hertz}\) low-pass filter. Short pulses are more unconditional, but filtering destroys the target displacement unless the waveform is precompensated.}
  \label{fig:entfilter}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Two-tone branch compensation is the best simple protocol}

The most successful physically interpretable strategy is the two-tone pulse of Eq.~(\ref{eq:twotone}). Solving the two-branch complex response equation yields a \(\SI{20}{\nano\second}\) pulse with
\begin{equation}
\delta\alpha = 8.15\times10^{-4},
\end{equation}
vacuum-branch fidelities above \(0.999996\), and residual superposition entanglement below \(10^{-5}\) bits. The corresponding vacuum superposition fidelity is \(0.997680\), essentially matching the best fast Gaussian pulse while providing a direct calibration interpretation in terms of branch frequencies and tone weights.

The two-tone pulse is also fairly insensitive to small branch-frequency calibration error. In the \(\SI{80}{\nano\second}\) robustness check, varying the branch-frequency offset by \(\pm 10\%\) changed the vacuum superposition fidelity only from \(0.973914\) to \(0.973759\). The present study therefore identifies two-tone compensation as the easiest experimentally calibratable route to high-quality unconditional displacement in this parameter regime.

\subsection{The echoed protocol underperforms because the qubit inversion is not manifold uniform}

The echoed family was intended to cancel the leading dispersive phase error by symmetry. That ideal toggling-frame argument does not survive the realistic waveform model. The best echoed case in the tested family occurs at total duration \(\SI{60}{\nano\second}\), but it still gives only
\begin{equation}
\delta\alpha = 0.0787,\quad F_{+x}=0.891,\quad S=0.0288\ \mathrm{bits}.
\end{equation}
The protocol is therefore clearly inferior to both the short fast pulse and the short two-tone solution.

The physical reason is straightforward: once the cavity has been displaced, the inserted qubit \(\pi\) pulse is no longer uniform across the populated cavity manifolds. Instead of canceling the conditionality cleanly, the echo introduces an additional number-dependent control error. This makes the practical echoed sequence a negative result for unconditional displacement, even though the ideal toggling-frame picture remains instructive.

\subsection{Constrained optimal control gives the best broad-set average fidelity}

Figure~\ref{fig:protocolsummary} summarizes the selected protocol comparison. The best overall mean state fidelity on the explicit broad test set is achieved by the constrained hardware-aware optimal-control pulse at \(\SI{40}{\nano\second}\),
\begin{equation}
\bar{F} = 0.957535,\qquad F_{\min}=0.874808.
\end{equation}
This protocol does not minimize the vacuum branch mismatch as aggressively as the best two-tone solution: its vacuum \(\delta\alpha\) is \(0.104776\), and the vacuum superposition fidelity is \(0.985303\). Its advantage comes instead from better balancing vacuum, low-Fock, and coherent-state performance under the included hardware constraints.

The comparison therefore has two winners, depending on the metric of interest.
\begin{itemize}
  \item The best simple and experimentally interpretable protocol is the \(\SI{20}{\nano\second}\) two-tone displacement.
  \item The best overall mean fidelity on the present broad state set comes from the constrained \(\SI{40}{\nano\second}\) optimal-control waveform.
\end{itemize}

\begin{figure}[tb]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{../figures/unconditional_protocol_summary.pdf}
  \caption{Compact protocol comparison using a common state-test-set mean fidelity, the vacuum branch mismatch, and the residual entanglement for the vacuum superposition input. The constrained optimal-control pulse gives the best overall mean fidelity on the broad state set, while the short two-tone pulse gives the best simple, physically interpretable unconditional displacement.}
  \label{fig:protocolsummary}
\end{figure}

\subsection{Wigner diagnostics confirm the physical picture}

Figure~\ref{fig:wigner} compares the reduced cavity Wigner functions for a representative failing case and a representative successful case, both starting from the vacuum superposition input. The naive \(\SI{80}{\nano\second}\) square pulse produces visibly different branch-conditioned cavity states and a correspondingly distorted reduced cavity state. By contrast, the two-tone pulse closely reproduces the ideal displaced cavity Wigner function.

\begin{figure}[tb]
  \centering
  \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{../figures/unconditional_wigner_comparison.pdf}
  \caption{Reduced cavity Wigner functions for a representative failure case (naive \(\SI{80}{\nano\second}\) square pulse) and a representative success case (two-tone compensated pulse). Each column shows the actual reduced cavity state for the vacuum superposition input and the corresponding ideal displaced cavity state. The naive pulse leaves a visibly distorted cavity state, whereas the two-tone pulse closely tracks the ideal displacement.}
  \label{fig:wigner}
\end{figure}

\section{Validation}
\label{sec:validation}

Three validation lanes were used.

\paragraph*{Sanity checks.}
In the ideal limit \(\chi=\chi'=K=0\), the square pulse recovers the unconditional displacement to numerical precision: the ideal-limit spot check gives \(\delta\alpha=0\) and vacuum superposition fidelity \(0.999985\). The naive protocol then departs continuously from that limit as \(|\chi|T\) increases, exactly as predicted by Eq.~(\ref{eq:squarebranch}).

\paragraph*{Mechanism isolation.}
At \(\alpha=1\) and \(T=\SI{80}{\nano\second}\), the model hierarchy gives \(\delta\alpha = 0.682\) in the minimal model, \(0.686\) after adding \(\chi'\), and \(0.686\) in the full model with Kerr. The dominant mechanism is therefore the leading dispersive pull \(\chi\), not the higher-order nonlinearities.

\paragraph*{Numerical convergence.}
A direct unconditional-displacement spot check for the representative naive \(\SI{80}{\nano\second}\) square pulse yields
\begin{itemize}
  \item \(n_{\mathrm{cav}} = 12,15,18 \rightarrow \delta\alpha = 0.685867, 0.685870, 0.685871\),
  \item \(n_{\mathrm{tr}} = 3,4 \rightarrow \delta\alpha = 0.685870, 0.685866\),
  \item \(\Delta t = 0.25, 0.5, 1.0~\si{\nano\second} \rightarrow \delta\alpha = 0.681879, 0.685870, 0.693775\).
\end{itemize}
These checks, together with the previously validated propagator settings for the same study family, support the numerical stability of the default choice \(n_{\mathrm{tr}}=3\), \(n_{\mathrm{cav}}=15\), and \(\Delta t=\SI{0.5}{\nano\second}\).

\section{Discussion And Experimental Relevance}
\label{sec:discussion}

The report's six central questions can now be answered directly.

\paragraph*{Why does the naive cavity pulse fail?}
Because the qubit-state-dependent dispersive pull detunes the cavity differently in the two branches. A pulse calibrated to be correct in one branch generally rotates and shrinks in the other, and a qubit superposition inherits the mismatch as residual qubit-cavity entanglement.

\paragraph*{How large is the error for realistic \(\chi\), \(\chi'\), Kerr, and duration?}
For the representative device parameters, the naive \(\SI{80}{\nano\second}\), \(\alpha=1\) square pulse already yields \(\delta\alpha=0.686\) and superposition fidelity \(0.770\). The hierarchy sweep shows that \(\chi'\) and Kerr only weakly perturb this number at the chosen operating point, so the main error scale is set by \(\chi\) and the pulse duration.

\paragraph*{Which protocol best approximates \(I_q \otimes D(\alpha)\)?}
On the explicit broad test set, the constrained optimal-control pulse is best. If the requirement is instead a simple and experimentally interpretable protocol, the short two-tone pulse is the preferred answer.

\paragraph*{Which protocol is easiest to calibrate experimentally?}
The two-tone strategy. It requires only branch-frequency estimation and a complex two-tone weight calibration, both of which can be tied directly to standard number-splitting and branch-conditioned displacement measurements.

\paragraph*{Can unconditional displacement be accurate enough for practical hybrid control?}
Yes, but only with explicit control design. The short Gaussian and short two-tone solutions both achieve vacuum superposition fidelities above \(0.997\), and the broad-set constrained optimal-control solution reaches \(0.958\) mean fidelity under realistic hardware constraints. A long naive pulse does not satisfy the same standard.

\paragraph*{When should one stop treating the pulse as unconditional?}
In the present parameter regime, naive pulses beyond roughly \(\SI{20}{\nano\second}\) already show measurable conditionality, and by \(\SI{80}{\nano\second}\) the operation is clearly a hybrid conditional process rather than a useful approximation to \(I_q \otimes D(\alpha)\). The natural warning scale is set by \(1/|\chi| \approx \SI{56}{\nano\second}\), but in practice the conservative threshold is shorter if high-fidelity superposition control is required.

\subsection{Calibration workflow for hardware}

The simulation results suggest a practical calibration path:
\begin{enumerate}
  \item Measure the effective cavity frequencies in the \(|g\rangle\) and \(|e\rangle\) manifolds, for example through branch-conditioned spectroscopy or number-splitting measurements~\cite{schuster2007resolving}.
  \item Calibrate the displacement amplitude in each branch separately.
  \item Solve for the relative two-tone amplitudes and phases that equalize the final displacement in the two branches.
  \item Validate the result on qubit superposition inputs using qubit tomography and branch-conditioned cavity tomography.
  \item Use Wigner tomography as the final cavity-state validation step.
\end{enumerate}
The same logic clarifies why the echo protocol is difficult experimentally: once the cavity is populated, the qubit inversion must be uniform across the relevant manifolds, which is a more demanding control problem than simple vacuum calibration.

\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

The unconditional displacement gate is not a native operation of a realistic dispersive qubit-cavity system; it is an approximation whose validity depends sharply on control design. In the present device regime, the naive single-tone picture fails once the duration approaches the dispersive timescale, and it fails most severely on the qubit superposition inputs that matter for hybrid quantum control. Two broad lessons follow.

First, the leading dispersive pull \(\chi\) is already enough to explain most of the failure. Second, the best fix depends on what one values most. If interpretability and calibratability are the priority, the short two-tone pulse is the best answer in this study. If broad-state performance under hardware constraints is the priority, the constrained optimal-control waveform performs best on the chosen benchmark set. In either case, the study shows that unconditional displacement can be made accurate enough for practical use, but not by relying on a long naive pulse.

\section{Limitations And Future Work}
\label{sec:limitations}

All reported simulations are unitary, so the protocol ranking should be interpreted as an upper bound on hardware performance. The optimal-control benchmark is intentionally bounded, not exhaustive: a larger basis, longer optimization, or richer training set could improve it further. The two-tone calibration objective is also vacuum focused, which explains why longer two-tone pulses can still degrade on coherent-state tests even when the vacuum branches are nearly equalized.

The most important follow-up directions are therefore clear. The study should be repeated with open-system noise channels, the short two-tone strategy should be combined with shaped or precompensated envelopes, and the optimal-control training set should be widened to include larger coherent amplitudes and nonclassical logical states. A manifold-uniform echoed displacement remains an interesting research problem, but the practical vacuum-calibrated echo tested here should not be treated as a competitive unconditional-displacement protocol.

